# API Rules

## Contract design
- Use resource-oriented naming and stable endpoint paths.
- Prefer additive contract changes; avoid breaking response fields.
- Version API when introducing breaking changes.

## Request/response consistency
- Use consistent pagination/filter/sort query parameters across endpoints.
- Return consistent envelope for success and error responses.
- Use HTTP status codes accurately (400/401/403/404/409/422/500).

## Validation and idempotency
- Validate request schema before controller logic.
- Enforce idempotency for create/payment/refund endpoints.
- Reject unknown/unsafe fields when writing domain data.

## Auth and authorization
- Separate authentication failure (401) from authorization failure (403).
- Check ownership/tenant boundaries for user-scoped resources.
- Protect admin endpoints with explicit role checks.

## Reliability and observability
- Add request correlation IDs for tracing.
- Log endpoint errors with route, actor, and request context.
- Keep API docs/examples in sync with implemented behavior.
